author: news@mpnews.net (Staff)
title: Mt. Pleasant boys are SEC cross country champions
text:
Mt. Pleasant boys are SEC cross country champions Oct 16, 2015 Photo by: Aaron Viner Logan Murray runs out in front of everyone at the SEC championships in Fairfield. Murray finished first and led the boys’ team to a conference title. 
BY ANDY KRUTSINGER 
Mt. Pleasant News 
WASHINGTON — The Mt. Pleasant cross country teams competed in the Southeastern Conference championship on Thursday night in Washington. The boys’ team had a dominant day, finishing with seven runners in the top 11 for first place. The girls’ finished fourth, ahead of Keokuk but behind Ft. Madison, Fairfield and Washington. 
On the boys’ side, Mt. Pleasant and Ft. Madison made up the entire top 11 finishers. Logan Murray won the meet by almost a full minute, finishing in 16:07. Adam Bodenham was the closest runner behind him, getting second, in 17:15. 
Kyle Vanderham and Cody Mertens placed fourth and fifth respectively to give the Panthers four top-five finishers. Vanderham ran the race in 17:35 and Mertens ran in 17:52. Ryan Hutchinson was eighth, in 18:06, Dalton Krum was ninth, in 28:08, and Jonathan Ita finished 11th, in 18:27. 
“I was very impressed to see us place four in the top five last night,” said head coach Mitch Anderson about the race. “All the boys raced well on a hilly course and windy night. To get four under 18 minutes again with the rest close was impressive. The boys should have confidence heading into the state qualifying meet.” 
The junior varsity boys also had a dominant performance, finishing with eight of the top nine runners. Ben Zihlman won the race, in 18:11. Jack Pieper, Jacob and Joseph Holtkamp and Dalton Moyle all finished in the top five. 
On the girls’ side, Taylor Murray, Delaney McDowell and Kelsey Notestein each finished in the top 20. Murray was ninth, in 21:31; McDowell was 14th, in 22:09, and Notestein was 20th, in 23:30. 
Catherine Prough took 26th place, in 24:33. Ally Davis was 28th, in 25:27, and Megan Shumaker and Megan Hoenig finished 30th and 31st, in 26:22 and 27:04 respectively. Emma Smith was the top junior varsity runner for the girls. She finished 11th for JV in 25:53. 
Girls’ head coach Jean Caboth said after the race that the seniors represented the team well and praised Emma Smith’s performance in the JV race. Caboth said the team “tried really hard to beat Washington” but it “was not to be.” 
The middle school teams also competed, and the MPCMS girls took home a conference title, led by Abby Ryon, who finished third overall but first among the SEC competitors, in 12:14.35. Kendall Dascher, Anna Ostby, Abby Jalas, Liz Perry and Claire Holtkamp each finished in the top 15. 
On the middle school boys’ side, the Panthers finished third and were led by Nick McCormick who finished seventh place, in 12:09. Drake Snavely and Heath Brooks ran 10th and 20th to give the Panthers three runners in the top 20. 
Next up for the Panthers is the state qualifying meet at Waterworks Park, in Fairfield. The meet has a set start time of 4 p.m.
